CS 255 Portfolio Reflection

This repository contains the Business Requirements Document and the System Design Document created for the DriverPass project. 
Together, these documents demonstrate my ability to gather customer requirements, analyze business needs, 
and translate those requirements into a complete system design using UML diagrams and supporting documentation.

Briefly summarize the DriverPass project. Who was the client? What type of system did they want you to design?

The DriverPass project focused on designing a web-based system for a company that provides driver's education and behind-the-wheel training. 
The client wanted a system that would allow students to register for accounts, schedule driving lessons, access online courses and practice tests, 
and stay up to date with DMV requirements. The business also needed tools for managing appointments, drivers, vehicles, user accounts, and reports while maintaining secure, role-based access for employees.

What did you do particularly well?

I believe my strongest work was translating the client's requirements into a structured system design. 
Rather than immediately thinking about implementation, I focused on understanding how the different users would interact with the system and how the different components would work together. 
Creating the UML diagrams helped me visualize those relationships before any code would be written. 
I also paid close attention to ensuring that each requirement mentioned during the client interview was represented somewhere in the final design.

If you could choose one part of your work on these documents to revise, what would you pick? How would you improve it?

If I were to revise one part of this project, I would spend more time refining the UML diagrams, particularly the class diagram. 
While it accurately represents the major classes and their relationships, I now have a much better understanding of object-oriented design than I did when I first created it. 
I would simplify some relationships, improve the organization of the diagram, and include methods where appropriate to better communicate how the classes interact. 
As I continue gaining experience with software architecture, I recognize that there are often multiple valid ways to model the same system, 
and I would use what I have learned to create a cleaner and more maintainable design.

How did you interpret the user's needs and implement them into your system design? Why is it so important to consider the user's needs when designing?

I interpreted the client's needs by identifying the primary goals of each type of user and then designing the system around those responsibilities. 
Students needed an easy way to register, schedule lessons, and access learning materials. Employees needed tools to manage appointments and customer information. 
The IT administrator required account management capabilities, while the owner needed reporting and oversight features. 
By separating these responsibilities into different parts of the system, I created a design that supports each user's role without giving unnecessary access to sensitive information.

Considering the user's needs is one of the most important parts of software design because the success of a system depends on whether it solves the customer's actual problems. 
A technically impressive application has little value if it does not support the workflows that users rely on every day. 
Understanding those needs before designing the system helps reduce rework later in the development process.

How do you approach designing software? What techniques or strategies would you use in the future to analyze and design a system?

This project reinforced the importance of designing software before writing code. I now approach software design by first understanding the problem, 
identifying the users, documenting the requirements, and breaking the system into smaller responsibilities. After gathering the requirements, 
I use diagrams such as use case, activity, sequence, and class diagrams to visualize how the system should function before implementation begins.

Going forward, I plan to continue using this structured approach. I have also learned the importance of building software incrementally, 
validating requirements throughout development, and revisiting the design as new information becomes available. Careful planning at the beginning of a project leads to cleaner code, 
fewer defects, and a system that is easier to maintain and expand in the future.
